events.event_name: Canada January 2026 Labour Force Survey Release
events.description: The release of Canada's unemployment and employment data for January 2026.

facts.fact_text: Canada's unemployment rate fell to 6.5% in January 2026.

evidences.evidence_text: The unemployment rate in Canada fell to 6.5% in January 2026 from 6.8% in the previous month

facts.fact_text: The Canadian labour force contracted by approximately 94,000 people.

evidences.evidence_text: The labour force contracted by roughly 94,000, pushing the participation rate down to 65.0% from 65.4%.

facts.fact_text: Net employment in Canada decreased by 25,000.

evidences.evidence_text: Net employment fell by 25,000 to 21.12 million, interrupting the recent run of gains.

facts.fact_text: Full-time employment increased by 45,000 while part-time employment fell by 70,000.

evidences.evidence_text: Losses were driven by a 70,000 decline in part-time employment, partly offset by a 45,000 increase in full-time work.

claims.claim_text: The drop in the unemployment rate was driven by fewer people searching for work.

evidences.evidence_text: marking the lowest level in 18 months, as fewer people searched for work.

claims.claim_text: The decline in the unemployment rate partially reversed the increase seen in the previous month.

evidences.evidence_text: The decline marked a partial reversal of the prior month’s increase
